1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:19,574
namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:19,554 --> 00:00:47,740
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa homage to the Buddha the blessed noble and fully self-enlightened one so we are carrying on with our the human condition this is the last one of this particular section which is called

3
00:00:47,990 --> 00:01:14,655
a world in turmoil greed hatred and delusion of every kind are unwholesome whatever action a greedy hating and deluded person keeps up by deeds words and thoughts that too is unwholesome whatever suffering such a person overpowered by greed hatred and delusion

4
00:01:15,057 --> 00:01:36,158
his thoughts controlled by them, inflicts under false pretexts upon another by killing, imprisonment, confiscation of property, false accusations or expulsion, being prompted in this by the thought, I have power and I want power, all this is unwholesome too.

5
00:01:38,079 --> 00:01:43,004
So this is one of those

6
00:01:43,710 --> 00:01:46,876
really pointed things as the Buddha talks about his power.

7
00:01:47,917 --> 00:01:51,162
Have to be careful here about power as such.

8
00:01:52,944 --> 00:02:07,364
If we look at our own history, our own psychoanalytic history, you find Freud thought that our main problem was pleasure, the pleasure principle.

9
00:02:08,205 --> 00:02:11,811
And then one of his students, Adler, thought it was power

10
00:02:12,145 --> 00:02:16,231
And another one, Frankl, I just looked these up on Wikipedia,

11
00:02:16,735 --> 00:02:21,902
I thought it was meaning, which is rather interesting actually.

12
00:02:21,923 --> 00:02:25,429
Our search for meaning was the driving force in our lives.

13
00:02:25,808 --> 00:02:28,993
So here you have three driving forces.

14
00:02:30,856 --> 00:02:34,603
Pleasure principle, wanting to be happy for heaven's sake.

15
00:02:34,622 --> 00:02:36,825
Power, power gives us control.

16
00:02:36,885 --> 00:02:40,532
And then meaning, why are we alive?

17
00:02:40,932 --> 00:02:41,854
Where are we going?

18
00:02:42,055 --> 00:02:42,895
Why were we born?

19
00:02:42,915 --> 00:02:43,637
All that sort of stuff.

20
00:02:45,423 --> 00:02:55,578
It's interesting to note that in the Buddha's history, in the Buddha's process, his main problem seemed to be around pleasure.

21
00:02:57,622 --> 00:03:00,265
Mara, the evil one, sent his three daughters.

22
00:03:01,026 --> 00:03:04,352
One was sensual pleasure, sexual pleasure, and boredom.

23
00:03:04,953 --> 00:03:06,435
That was his problem, you see.

24
00:03:06,787 --> 00:03:15,901
If you compare that to Christ, Jesus Christ, remember he was taken to the top of the mountain by Satan and given power over all.

25
00:03:15,942 --> 00:03:18,586
His was a power complex.

26
00:03:18,686 --> 00:03:19,967
Very interesting, huh?

27
00:03:20,008 --> 00:03:22,752
The contrast between those two great spiritual leaders.

28
00:03:25,837 --> 00:03:28,200
Then you get all sorts of ideas about power.

29
00:03:29,103 --> 00:03:32,929
Even, say, Nietzsche, who had such an influence on

30
00:03:33,500 --> 00:03:44,776
you know, the Nazis and people like that, that drive of will to power, the will to be the best you could be, that's another one, isn't it?

31
00:03:44,997 --> 00:03:47,901
Driven by the idea of being the best.

32
00:03:50,645 --> 00:03:59,877
And then you get people like Schopenhauer, I think, the will to live, just to be alive,

33
00:04:00,026 --> 00:04:04,912
I mean, we come across that when our lives are in danger, you know, you just want to be alive for God's sake.

34
00:04:06,894 --> 00:04:10,157
So there are all these types of power.

35
00:04:11,118 --> 00:04:16,283
When it comes to the Buddha's teachings, we have a positive power.

36
00:04:18,526 --> 00:04:24,632
They're called the Iddhipada, the paths of power, accompanied by the effect of will.

37
00:04:25,915 --> 00:04:29,038
One of them is desire, intention.

38
00:04:29,456 --> 00:04:33,605
So remember, you can have a desire to become liberated from suffering.

39
00:04:34,105 --> 00:04:38,754
Unless your will is behind it, unless there's a real power, nothing's going to happen.

40
00:04:38,894 --> 00:04:40,096
You're going to sit there dreaming.

41
00:04:42,040 --> 00:04:42,800
And there's energy.

42
00:04:43,642 --> 00:04:50,334
So it's a real, what the Buddha's saying is, to progress spiritually, you've got to have a real energy, a real power behind that energy.

43
00:04:51,596 --> 00:04:53,119
And then there's the heart.

44
00:04:53,199 --> 00:04:54,781
Your heart's got to be empowered.

45
00:04:55,262 --> 00:04:59,507
There's got to be a real inner desire to become liberated.

46
00:05:00,548 --> 00:05:03,853
And then finally there has to be this quality of investigation.

47
00:05:04,372 --> 00:05:09,540
Because our problem fundamentally is delusion and misunderstanding somewhere.

48
00:05:09,939 --> 00:05:18,050
So we have to search within our lives with the way we think, what we do, where are we going wrong, how are we creating problems for ourselves.

49
00:05:18,071 --> 00:05:20,793
So that has to be really empowered.

50
00:05:21,382 --> 00:05:24,004
So these are all the positive sides of power.

51
00:05:24,024 --> 00:05:29,271
But I think here of course the Buddha is saying that there is such a power which is driven by greed, hatred and delusion.

52
00:05:29,793 --> 00:05:31,415
That's obviously we talk about something else.

53
00:05:33,096 --> 00:05:49,819
And then he says it is whatever suffering such a person overpowered by greed, hatred and delusion his thoughts controlled by them inflicts under false pretext upon another

54
00:05:50,288 --> 00:05:55,213
by killing, imprisonment, confiscation of property, false accusation and expulsion.

55
00:05:55,913 --> 00:06:00,019
Being prompted in this by the thought, I have power and I want power.

56
00:06:00,439 --> 00:06:03,142
So obviously that's a completely different form of power.

57
00:06:03,182 --> 00:06:06,065
That's a power which is coming from control, isn't it?

58
00:06:07,648 --> 00:06:13,995
Of getting what you want at the expense of anybody or anything, even the earth.

59
00:06:14,014 --> 00:06:18,540
To understand that we have to go back to this basic idea of the self itself.

60
00:06:18,858 --> 00:06:32,714
and who we think we are so remember that our essential delusion is a problem of identity of who we are and having defined ourselves as human beings

61
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:38,271
You see, this is a big problem because now we're searching absolute or real happiness as a human being.

62
00:06:38,891 --> 00:06:53,117
In so doing, we have a relationship to the world of making sure the world, through the body, through the world that we can find happiness and that we want to control the world, you see.

63
00:06:53,519 --> 00:06:55,882
So you either control it by getting rich.

64
00:06:56,783 --> 00:06:58,305
That's one way of trying to control it.

65
00:06:59,588 --> 00:06:59,947
Fame.

66
00:07:01,430 --> 00:07:03,913
Being famous is a lovely feeling.

67
00:07:03,994 --> 00:07:06,117
Being loved, even though it's not a real love.

68
00:07:06,658 --> 00:07:09,201
People drop you as soon as you're not making up the right songs.

69
00:07:09,802 --> 00:07:15,992
So fame is very flimsy, but it gives you a feeling of being wanted.

70
00:07:17,754 --> 00:07:21,399
And you have a control over your fans.

71
00:07:22,612 --> 00:07:24,740
And then, of course, there's just naked power.

72
00:07:25,081 --> 00:07:26,425
Just power.

73
00:07:27,288 --> 00:07:31,403
And we have lots of examples in our own history of that.

74
00:07:31,483 --> 00:07:33,069
Machiavelli was the one, wasn't he?

75
00:07:33,110 --> 00:07:34,072
Machiavelli was the...

76
00:07:34,524 --> 00:07:40,857
The Renaissance thinker who said, if you want to be a good ruler, forget love, fear.

77
00:07:41,458 --> 00:07:44,244
Fear was the way to keep control.

78
00:07:44,865 --> 00:07:53,360
And of course, if you look at just around the world, the dictators we have still, this terrible thing going on in Syria.

79
00:07:53,999 --> 00:08:05,250
So all these are people who've gained power and who gather support for their power by making sure that everybody has a little share of the goods.

80
00:08:05,812 --> 00:08:07,372
That's how you get your support, isn't it?

81
00:08:08,774 --> 00:08:15,601
So if you're a dictator, you want to make sure that your army gets exactly what it needs and what it wants and your soldiers have a good night out.

82
00:08:16,702 --> 00:08:22,369
And then they've got something to lose, in which case, of course, they'll be right behind you.

83
00:08:22,973 --> 00:08:27,800
And they definitely don't want the opposition to win, because they will take power.

84
00:08:28,180 --> 00:08:29,161
See, that's the awful thing.

85
00:08:29,221 --> 00:08:39,195
If you compare, for instance, what's happened in Burma, or, well, take Burma just for an instance, where the opposition has been non-violent.

86
00:08:40,297 --> 00:08:47,547
See, because it's been non-violent, eventually, even though it's caused sacrifice, that's the problem with non-violence, it demands sacrifice.

87
00:08:48,168 --> 00:08:53,298
After all the killing, eventually the military, the dictator, begins to give way.

88
00:08:53,357 --> 00:08:58,586
It's the same with India, with Gandhi and the British.

89
00:08:59,589 --> 00:09:04,558
It's a non-violence and eventually it just gives way, even though there's sacrifice.

90
00:09:04,578 --> 00:09:11,711
But when you're into some violent revolution, such as what's happening in Syria, then of course you have many more deaths actually because of that.

91
00:09:13,278 --> 00:09:21,126
Because it's two people facing each other with the desire for absolute power.

92
00:09:22,207 --> 00:09:23,850
Both sides want to destroy the other.

93
00:09:25,130 --> 00:09:28,695
There's not going to be much chance for peace if you're going to do that.

94
00:09:29,355 --> 00:09:35,702
If you look at South Africa and the whole way that Nelson Mandela was seen, towards reconciliation.

95
00:09:36,283 --> 00:09:40,347
But there has to be, this is the problem, there has to be that sacrifice.

96
00:09:40,565 --> 00:10:01,323
most people don't want to do that they'd rather just go for the enemy and that's the end of that so power in terms of our lives so really we have to see where is it that we're exercising power in this bad sense trying to control people

97
00:10:02,772 --> 00:10:10,664
We can do it very cleverly, by hints and by emotional blackmail, you know.

98
00:10:11,306 --> 00:10:13,789
I will not love you unless you give me everything I need.

99
00:10:15,952 --> 00:10:20,139
And there's just naked power, money power, you know.

100
00:10:22,703 --> 00:10:30,096
Just to investigate our relationships and the way that because we depend on these relationships for happiness, see,

101
00:10:30,397 --> 00:10:32,720
Not to say that there isn't a true love there.

102
00:10:33,100 --> 00:10:35,884
It doesn't negate the fact that there is a true love there.

103
00:10:36,304 --> 00:10:40,652
It's just that there's another bit which is about this relationship is for me.

104
00:10:40,892 --> 00:10:41,513
Am I you?

105
00:10:42,835 --> 00:10:44,277
And that's where you get the power.

106
00:10:44,778 --> 00:10:46,100
That's where you want the control.

107
00:10:46,580 --> 00:10:53,509
So parents definitely love their children but they also want to be able to tell their children what to do.

108
00:10:53,549 --> 00:10:58,918
Not so much for the benefit of the child but for their benefit.

109
00:10:58,982 --> 00:11:09,274
So the worst case is, you know, when somebody, I remember seeing a program where a parent, she'd failed to become the violinist that she wanted to be.

110
00:11:09,855 --> 00:11:17,123
And so by every means she could, her daughter was going to be this great violinist.

111
00:11:17,143 --> 00:11:20,606
And of course it was just messing the daughter up.

112
00:11:20,626 --> 00:11:24,871
So it's an imposition, you see, an imposition of her desire on the other.

113
00:11:25,307 --> 00:11:28,793
So this is where power causes us problems in our lives.

114
00:11:31,155 --> 00:11:43,432
And eventually, of course, we might end up doing exactly what the Buddha says here, inflicts under false pretext upon another, killing, imprisonment, confiscation of property, false accusation and expulsion.

115
00:11:44,073 --> 00:11:44,835
Terrible.

116
00:11:46,418 --> 00:12:05,888
So I hope my words have been of some assistance and that overcoming all temptation to control, to control, to have power in a bad sense, you will achieve full liberation from suffering sooner rather than later.

117
00:12:10,394 --> 00:12:11,196
Thank you very much.

118
00:12:13,879 --> 00:12:15,042
Any comments on that?

119
00:12:22,024 --> 00:12:23,347
Any ideas?

120
00:12:25,451 --> 00:12:34,929
Some sort of clarification about the difference between tango and chaitanya.

121
00:12:34,990 --> 00:12:44,168
Is it the delusion and the ego identification which is the problem which turns something neutral into something bad?

122
00:12:44,957 --> 00:12:47,201
Yeah, yeah.

123
00:12:48,523 --> 00:12:52,089
The word tanha that you've used is a specific meaning.

124
00:12:52,149 --> 00:12:56,855
It has a specific meaning of a desire which is unwholesome, unskillful.

125
00:12:57,756 --> 00:13:02,202
The word for a desire, generally speaking, is chandra.

126
00:13:02,243 --> 00:13:07,932
So that's the word they use in those paths to power that I was talking about.

127
00:13:07,951 --> 00:13:13,480
So the desire to become liberated, that would be considered wholesome, I think.

128
00:13:14,793 --> 00:13:32,042
and one has to empower that desire you want to really you want to really need that you're seeking for liberation from suffering so that's satana chaitanya is something else chaitanya is the will so that's the power that's that's power you see so for instance you can intend

129
00:13:32,342 --> 00:13:33,823
But nothing may happen.

130
00:13:34,565 --> 00:13:39,710
So you can intend, for instance, well now we'll intend to have a cup of tea.

131
00:13:40,250 --> 00:13:45,355
But if it's not empowered, you'll just be sitting here still intending till tomorrow morning.

132
00:13:46,376 --> 00:13:50,701
So the power is what takes something out of potential into an actual.

133
00:13:51,422 --> 00:13:53,825
And that's an actual, that's a force.

134
00:13:55,787 --> 00:14:02,113
I mean, I can intend to move the chair, but unless I actually put energy into it, it's not going to happen.

135
00:14:02,514 --> 00:14:05,000
So that's the power there.

136
00:14:05,381 --> 00:14:07,606
Now, power itself is completely neutral.

137
00:14:08,730 --> 00:14:11,596
What makes it wholesome and unwholesome is the attitude driving it.

138
00:14:12,759 --> 00:14:16,346
So if you want to make somebody suffer, you'll use your power to do that.

139
00:14:16,607 --> 00:14:20,456
If you want to make somebody happy, you'll use your power to do that.

140
00:14:21,162 --> 00:14:39,828
and then there's also just generally speaking two types of power that we can wield we have the word authority so you can be in authority over so to be in authority over somebody you inspire fear

141
00:14:40,315 --> 00:14:44,380
But you can also be an authority whereby you inspire respect.

142
00:14:44,721 --> 00:14:52,371
If you're somebody who people think is an authority, like when you go to the doctor, hopefully, you think it's an authority.

143
00:14:52,452 --> 00:14:53,474
They've got to be right.

144
00:14:54,455 --> 00:14:55,216
So there's that.

145
00:14:55,236 --> 00:14:58,201
There's a completely different sort of relationship there, you see.

146
00:14:59,361 --> 00:15:01,125
Most positions have a bit of both.

147
00:15:01,256 --> 00:15:10,650
to have a bit of power with being an authority is often necessary to get done what you need to be done, what needs to be done, you see.

148
00:15:11,471 --> 00:15:17,441
But you can see there's a distinction there between two types of power that's often invested in us.

149
00:15:18,361 --> 00:15:22,869
And remember that dictators only arise because people invest them with power.

150
00:15:24,591 --> 00:15:27,735
And it wouldn't happen if people didn't give them the power that they had.

151
00:15:28,557 --> 00:15:29,778
Take Cameron, for instance.

152
00:15:30,248 --> 00:15:53,927
we've given him power for five years so that's that and going back to your original point about the self well the self remember is in the Buddhist terms it's a relationship when we say I am when you finish off that sentence

153
00:15:54,480 --> 00:15:56,484
That's telling you something about yourself.

154
00:15:56,504 --> 00:15:58,746
So it could be something like, I am depressed.

155
00:15:59,167 --> 00:16:01,410
So now this is me, I am depressed.

156
00:16:01,431 --> 00:16:05,115
See, once you identify with something, there's no escape, is there?

157
00:16:05,135 --> 00:16:05,775
What are you going to do?

158
00:16:05,917 --> 00:16:06,638
I am depressed.

159
00:16:07,519 --> 00:16:15,350
See, I mean, what we're learning here is that we see depression as something outside the I, outside this observer.

160
00:16:15,830 --> 00:16:19,274
So it's more accurate to say, there is depression.

161
00:16:20,216 --> 00:16:23,660
Now that liberates, that liberates me from suffering the depression.

162
00:16:24,147 --> 00:16:48,450
doesn't make any it doesn't it doesn't take away the depression the depression still remains a depression but now I can find another identity which is no matter what no matter that there's a feeling of depression I'll carry on doing what I need to do see it won't it won't hijack my life so and then there are definitions like I know

163
00:16:48,734 --> 00:17:16,142
I'm an electrician, I'm a teacher, I'm a doctor so when these are taken away from us then of course you get depression I mean once you lose your job and you say I am but if you take the I away and say that that there is an action of being an electrician or whatever it is then there's not that identity you see

164
00:17:16,425 --> 00:17:22,255
So if it goes away, you still don't lose that sense of self-esteem.

165
00:17:23,096 --> 00:17:24,136
That's the point.

166
00:17:24,156 --> 00:17:30,507
If your self-esteem is based on your job and your job goes, then you lose your self-esteem.

167
00:17:30,567 --> 00:17:33,351
You feel diminished by it.

168
00:17:35,713 --> 00:17:39,480
It's the same with watching these Paralympics.

169
00:17:40,117 --> 00:17:52,553
These people, some of them have had really bad accidents, suffered greatly, but you can see they've all regained a lot of their self-esteem, which they might have lost through becoming disabled.

170
00:17:54,434 --> 00:18:00,742
Because before you said, I am a fully able person, and now you've got to go around saying, I am disabled.

171
00:18:00,782 --> 00:18:05,248
That's a loss of something, isn't it?

172
00:18:07,539 --> 00:18:25,683
so that's what the self is the self is is when you complete the sentence I am right hey there's a problem if you check if you take that I am away and say there is there's a completely different relationship

173
00:18:35,198 --> 00:19:03,400
it's the same with a lesser sense of identity which is I have see I own owning objects if you think about it actually you can only use an object you can't in any absolute sense own it I mean legally you might say this is my car but when the thief takes it it's his like it's not yours anymore you still go around saying somebody's stolen my car

174
00:19:04,527 --> 00:19:07,691
But that's just a legal fiction.

175
00:19:14,660 --> 00:19:22,630
It's like something that you might, I don't know, you might get some precious glassware or something like that, you see.

176
00:19:23,592 --> 00:19:25,914
And it's my glassware, you see.

177
00:19:26,816 --> 00:19:27,836
It's something that you possess.

178
00:19:27,916 --> 00:19:29,519
If it breaks, of course, a lot of suffering.

179
00:19:30,160 --> 00:19:32,542
But if you already see it broken...

180
00:19:32,741 --> 00:19:34,984
When it breaks, well, it's going to break anyway.

181
00:19:35,224 --> 00:19:36,007
I saw it broken.

182
00:19:37,288 --> 00:19:44,137
It's like getting a different relationship with things so that when they disappear, it doesn't hurt.

183
00:19:44,157 --> 00:19:46,221
Or it doesn't hurt so much.

184
00:19:47,962 --> 00:19:57,797
Self-remembering is then something which is opposite to self-identifying.

185
00:19:57,817 --> 00:20:00,740
Well, self-remembering is, yes, I mean, self-remembering

186
00:20:01,108 --> 00:20:19,371
dissociating ourselves from

187
00:20:19,772 --> 00:20:21,517
Yes, but you have to be careful with that word.

188
00:20:21,596 --> 00:20:27,310
Primarily it's a dissociation to get away from the wrong relationship.

189
00:20:27,330 --> 00:20:30,699
But then you have to re-engage with the right relationship.

190
00:20:30,739 --> 00:20:31,200
See?

191
00:20:31,535 --> 00:20:36,882
So you might say, for instance, you might dissociate yourself from somebody's suffering.

192
00:20:37,021 --> 00:20:39,744
And you might say, well, that's their karma.

193
00:20:39,765 --> 00:20:40,465
What's it got to do with me?

194
00:20:40,486 --> 00:20:41,086
It's their karma.

195
00:20:43,009 --> 00:20:47,914
But then you've got to re-engage and recognize that we're all in this together.

196
00:20:48,395 --> 00:20:52,580
And there comes that compassion and a desire to alleviate suffering.

197
00:20:53,489 --> 00:21:06,063
I always like to tell the story of when I was in Thailand and I went to visit this monk and there was a cat and it was playing around with a mouse which was already dead.

198
00:21:07,223 --> 00:21:09,307
And I just said to him, I said, didn't you stop that?

199
00:21:09,346 --> 00:21:10,028
It's a fat cat.

200
00:21:10,607 --> 00:21:13,230
You know, it's a monastery cat.

201
00:21:13,652 --> 00:21:14,532
It's a fat cat.

202
00:21:14,553 --> 00:21:15,473
I said, didn't you stop that?

203
00:21:16,295 --> 00:21:16,914
He said, no.

204
00:21:16,934 --> 00:21:18,436
He said, it's cat karma, mouse karma.

205
00:21:19,919 --> 00:21:19,999
See?

206
00:21:20,019 --> 00:21:22,922
So I said, that is... And funnily enough,

207
00:21:23,222 --> 00:21:31,496
Funnily enough, very shortly after that, I was sitting on a bench with a few monks, and this cat jumped out and caught a bird.

208
00:21:31,635 --> 00:21:47,442
